page_title: Quickstart: Use Azure OpenAI Service with PowerShell
page_description: Walkthrough on how to get started with Azure OpenAI and make your first completions call with PowerShell.
chunk_content: Output```powershell# the output of the script will be a .NET object containing the responseid      : chatcmpl-7sdJJRC6fDNGnfHMdfHXvPkYFbaVcobject  : chat.completioncreated : 1693255177model   : gpt-35-turbochoices : {@{index=0; finish_reason=stop; message=}}usage   : @{completion_tokens=67; prompt_tokens=55; total_tokens=122}# convert the output to JSON./quickstart.ps1 | ConvertTo-Json -Depth 3# or to view the text returned, select the specific object property$reponse = ./quickstart.ps1$response.choices.message.content```> [!div class="nextstepaction"]> I ran into an issue when running the code sample.### Understanding the message structureThe GPT-35-Turbo and GPT-4 models are optimized to work with inputs formatted as a conversation. The `messages` variable passes an array of dictionaries with different roles in the conversation delineated by system, user, and assistant. The system message can be used to prime the model by including context or instructions on how the model should respond.The GPT-35-Turbo & GPT-4 how-to guide provides an in-depth introduction into the options for communicating with these new models.
